# JWT Refresh Token Tests
# Use with REST Client extension in VS Code

@baseUrl = http://localhost:3000/api/v1
@accessToken = 
@refreshToken = 

### 1. Login - Get Access & Refresh Tokens
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "admin@hotel.com",
  "password": "admin123"
}

# Response:
# {
#   "accessToken": "eyJhbG...", (expires in 15 minutes)
#   "refreshToken": "3a6351e50...", (expires in 7 days)
#   "user": { ... }
# }

### 2. Refresh Token - Get New Token Pair
# Use the refresh token from login response
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/refresh
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "refreshToken": "{{refreshToken}}"
}

# Response:
# {
#   "accessToken": "eyJhbG...", (new token)
#   "refreshToken": "c6ca48b4..." (new refresh token, old one revoked)
# }

### 3. Try to Reuse Old Refresh Token (Should Fail)
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/refresh
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "refreshToken": "old_token_here"
}

# Expected: 401 Unauthorized
# Response: { "error": "Invalid or expired refresh token" }

### 4. Access Protected Route with Access Token
GET {{baseUrl}}/auth/me
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

# Response: User profile data

### 5. Logout - Revoke Specific Refresh Token
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/logout
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "refreshToken": "{{refreshToken}}"
}

# Response: { "message": "Logged out successfully" }

### 6. Login from Multiple Devices
# Login #1 (Desktop)
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "frontdesk@hotel.com",
  "password": "staff123"
}

###
# Login #2 (Mobile)
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "frontdesk@hotel.com",
  "password": "staff123"
}

###
# Login #3 (Tablet)
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "frontdesk@hotel.com",
  "password": "staff123"
}

### 7. Logout from All Devices
# Revokes ALL refresh tokens for the user
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/logout-all
Authorization: Bearer {{accessToken}}

# Response: { "message": "Logged out from all devices successfully" }

### 8. Test Token Expiry
# Wait 15+ minutes, then try to access protected route
# The access token should be expired
GET {{baseUrl}}/auth/me
Authorization: Bearer expired_token_here

# Expected: 401 Unauthorized
# Response: { "error": "Token expired" }

### 9. Use Refresh Token After Expiry
# After 7 days, the refresh token should also expire
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/refresh
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "refreshToken": "expired_refresh_token"
}

# Expected: 401 Unauthorized
# Response: { "error": "Invalid or expired refresh token" }

### 10. Test Registration with Token Pair
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/register
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "newstaff@hotel.com",
  "password": "password123",
  "firstName": "New",
  "lastName": "Staff",
  "phoneNumber": "+1-555-9999",
  "role": "FRONT_DESK"
}

# Response:
# {
#   "accessToken": "eyJhbG...",
#   "refreshToken": "3a6351e50...",
#   "user": { ... }
# }

### Token Lifecycle Summary
# 
# 1. Login → Receive accessToken (15m) + refreshToken (7d)
# 2. Use accessToken for API requests
# 3. When accessToken expires → Use refreshToken to get new pair
# 4. Token Rotation: Old refreshToken revoked, new one issued
# 5. Logout → Revoke specific refreshToken
# 6. Logout-all → Revoke ALL refreshTokens for user
# 7. Expired tokens auto-deleted every 24 hours

### Security Features
#
# ✅ Access tokens expire in 15 minutes
# ✅ Refresh tokens expire in 7 days
# ✅ Tokens stored in MongoDB with expiry tracking
# ✅ Token rotation: Old token revoked when new one issued
# ✅ isRevoked flag prevents reuse of compromised tokens
# ✅ Logout-all revokes all sessions (security feature)
# ✅ Automatic cleanup of expired tokens
# ✅ Audit logging for login/logout events
